04868nam a22006975i 9780271080147DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710801477 a10.1515/97802710801472doi  a(DE-B1597)583974  a(OCoLC)1269268739  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aML3556b.D33 2016eb 7aMUS0180002bisacsh04a780.89/960732231 aDarden, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNothing but Love in God's Water :bVolume 2: Black Sacred Music from Sit-Ins to Resurrection City /cRobert Darden. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b28 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSpecial Thanks -- tIntroduction: What Came Before -- t1 The Sit- Ins -- t2 The Freedom Rides -- t3 Albany, Georgia -- t4 Birmingham, Alabama -- t5 The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom -- t6 Mississippi Freedom Summer -- t7 Selma, Alabama -- t8 Chicago, Illinois -- t9 Memphis, Tennessee -- tEpilogue -- tAfterword: What Comes Now -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVolume 1 of Nothing but Love in God's Water traced the music of protest spirituals from the Civil War to the American labor movement of the 1930s and 1940s, and on through the Montgomery bus boycott. This second volume continues the journey, chronicling the role this music played in energizing and sustaining those most heavily involved in the civil rights movement.Robert Darden, former gospel music editor for Billboard magazine and the founder of the Black Gospel Music Restoration Project at Baylor University, brings this vivid, vital story to life. He explains why black sacred music helped foster community within the civil rights movement and attract new adherents; shows how Martin Luther King Jr. and other leaders used music to underscore and support their message; and reveals how the songs themselves traveled and changed as the fight for freedom for African Americans continued. Darden makes an unassailable case for the importance of black sacred music not only to the civil rights era but also to present-day struggles in and beyond the United States.Taking us from the Deep South to Chicago and on to the nation's capital, Darden's grittily detailed, lively telling is peppered throughout with the words of those who were there, famous and forgotten alike: activists such as Rep. John Lewis, the Reverend Ralph Abernathy, and Willie Bolden, as well as musical virtuosos such as Harry Belafonte, Duke Ellington, and The Mighty Wonders. Expertly assembled from published and unpublished writing, oral histories, and rare recordings, this is the history of the soundtrack that fueled the long march toward freedom and equality for the black community in the United States and that continues to inspire and uplift people all over the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryxCriticism, interpretation, etcxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aGospel musicxHistory and criticism. 0aSpirituals (Songs)xHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Religious / Gospel.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074524540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271080147zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271080147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271080147/original  a978-3-11-074524-5  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUA